description: From Middle English quenchinge, equivalent to quench +‎ -ing.

entries.meaning: (physics) The extinction of any of several physical properties.
(metallurgy) The rapid cooling of a hot metal object, by placing it in a liquid, in order to harden it.
(astronomy) A process in which a galaxy loses cold gas, thus strongly suppressing star formation.
(botany) The dissipation of energy from light in excess of what can be used for photosynthesis.
examples: When a leaf is in full sunshine, it absorbs more light energy than its photosynthetic machinery can handle. This damages cells unless they turn on a mechanism known as quenching to dissipate the excess energy.
When a leaf is shaded, however, quenching has to be turned off to avoid dissipating energy that could be used.

description: From Middle English quenching, quenchyng, quenchand, quenchende, equivalent to quench +‎ -ing.
